  "prompt": "What would happen if a DC motor was supplied with AC and vice-versa?",
  "response": "Let's analyze what happens when a DC motor is supplied with AC and vice versa:\n\nDC Motor with AC Supply:\n1. DC motors have commutators designed for unidirectional current\n2. AC will cause rapid polarity changes in the winding\n3. Consequences:\n- Erratic and inefficient rotation\n- High heat generation\n- Potential motor damage\n- Reduced torque and speed\n- Possible sparking at commutator\n\nAC Motor with DC Supply:\n1. AC motors rely on rotating magnetic fields\n2. DC provides constant magnetic field\n3. Consequences:\n- Motor will not start rotating\n- No electromagnetic field alternation\n- No torque generation\n- Static winding energization\n- Potential winding burnout if sustained\n\nKey Differences:\n- DC motors require unidirectional current\n- AC motors require alternating current\n- Different winding and magnetic field design\n- Incompatible electrical characteristics\n\nIn both scenarios, operating a motor with inappropriate power supply can cause:\n- Mechanical stress\n- Electrical damage\n- Reduced performance\n- Potential complete motor failure\n\nRecommendation:\nAlways use motors with their intended power supply type.",
